question:
Find $M^2+(A^T\cdot B)^{-1}$, where $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 3 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-2 & 4 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$, and $M=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
7 & 2 & 1 \\
-1 & 3 & 0  \\
2 & 0 & -2 \end{array}
\right)$.

Find $a$ such that the matrix $\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 2 & 3 \\ 
4 & 5 & 6 \\ 
3 & 2 & a \end{array}
\right)$ is singular.

Find $x$ and $y$ such that $\left( \begin{array}{rr}
-2 & 1 \\ 
3 & -4 \end{array}
\right)\left( \begin{array}{rr}
x & 2 \\ 
1 & y \end{array}
\right)=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
-3 & 1 \\ 
2 & -14 \end{array}
\right)$.
